Section not completed</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-6330606254.1255782b63dfba</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2011</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>'Not mine, not mine' : on the coffin question in non-religious funerals</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>A5B31C59-2D56-496F-8D03-377BD0CFB308</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This lecture addressed the ways in which humanist celebrants approach the presence of the coffin in the funerals they conduct. For some celebrants, addressing the coffin, or otherwise acknowledging its presence, seems illogical, since the point of a humanist funeral is to affirm the idea that there is no afterlife. So what is being addressed in such a situation? For other celebrants, the point is to show respect for the loved ones of the deceased. This paper situates these concerns in relation to broader literatures on material culture and the body.

This was worked up into a peer-review article which is forthcoming in June 2015.</gtr:impact><gtr:outcomeId>r-3761887851.88075922b124f6a</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Professional Practitioners</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2012</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>In spite of Christianity : humanism and its others in contemporary Britain</gtr:description><gtr:form>A talk or presentation</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>A39AAEA1-3D6B-4592-96CA-466F149FA108</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This was the Non-Religion and Secularity Research Network Annual Lecture, delivered to an audience of academics, students, and interested members of the general public. It was subsequently worked into an academic seminar paper and delivered at the 147th Wenner-Gren Foundation workshop in Sintra, Portugal.

